title: Electoral system of Australia
text: The electoral system of Australia uses a preferential voting system known as the Australian Electoral System. In this system, voters rank candidates in order of preference on their ballots. title: Vesicle (biology and chemistry)

Vesicles can be involved in processes such as exocytosis, endocytosis, and intracellular transport. They can also store and release neurotransmitters in nerve cells. Vesicles are essential for the proper functioning of cells and are found in nearly all types of cells, ranging from simple prokaryotic cells to complex eukaryotic cells.

title: Anti-Confederation Party

title: Von Neumann universe
text: The Von Neumann universe, named after mathematician John von Neumann, is a concept in set theory that describes a hierarchy of all sets. It is constructed by starting with the empty set, then considering sets of all previous stages. Each stage is obtained by taking the power set of the previous stage, resulting in a transfinite sequence of sets. The Von Neumann universe plays a fundamental role in modern mathematics and logic, providing a foundation for understanding the concept of sets and their properties.

title: Proplyd
text: A proplyd, short for protoplanetary disk, is a rotating disk of dense gas and dust surrounding a young star. These structures are commonly found in star-forming regions and play a crucial role in the formation of planets. As the proplyd’s material collides and clumps together, it can eventually lead to the creation of planetary bodies. Studying proplyds can provide valuable insights into the early stages of planetary formation and the dynamics of young stellar systems. Scientists use various telescopes and imaging techniques to observe and learn more about these fascinating cosmic objects.

title: Warsaw Uprising

title: Gunn–Peterson trough
text: The Gunn-Peterson trough, named after James E. Gunn and Bruce Peterson, is a feature observed in the spectra of distant quasars. It represents a nearly complete absorption of high energy Lyman-alpha photons by neutral hydrogen in the intergalactic medium, indicating a lack of ionized gas in the early universe. This phenomenon provides valuable insights into the reionization process and the evolution of structure in the universe. The discovery of the Gunn-Peterson trough has significantly contributed to our understanding of the cosmic timeline and the formation of galaxies.

Originating in Alexandria, Egypt, this text-type is known for its close attention to accuracy and precision in the copying of biblical texts. Scholars have identified key characteristics such as shorter readings, smoother grammar, and harmonized versions of parallel passages. The Alexandrian text-type is highly valued by many biblical scholars for its reliability in preserving the original words and meanings of the New Testament. It has been influential in the development of modern critical editions of the Greek New Testament.

title: Instant coffee
text: Instant coffee is a popular alternative to brewed coffee due to its convenience and quick preparation. It is made by freeze-drying or spray-drying brewed coffee, resulting in a powder that can be easily dissolved in hot water. Instant coffee has a longer shelf life compared to freshly brewed coffee and is often chosen for its portability and easy storage. While some may argue that the flavor of instant coffee is not as rich as brewed coffee, it remains a convenient option for those seeking a quick caffeine fix.

title: Free Church of Scotland (1843–1900)
text: The Free Church of Scotland was a Scottish denomination formed in 1843 following the Disruption of the Church of Scotland. Led by ministers and congregations who left the established church due to concerns over the interference of the state in ecclesiastical affairs, the Free Church sought to maintain the purity of Presbyterianism. Operating independently until its reunification with the Church of Scotland in 1900, the Free Church of Scotland played a significant role in shaping Scottish religious life during the 19th century. Its legacy continues to be felt in the Presbyterian tradition in Scotland today.

title: Bughouse chess
text: Bughouse chess, also known as exchange chess or Siamese chess, is a popular variant of the traditional game. In bughouse, four players divide into two teams, with each player having a teammate. This dynamic game requires quick thinking, teamwork, and strategic coordination between partners. Bughouse chess is a fast-paced and exciting way to enjoy the classic game of chess with a unique twist.

title: Vitalism
text: Vitalism is a philosophical theory that suggests living organisms are fundamentally different from non-living entities due to the presence of a vital principle or force. This concept, popular in the 18th and 19th centuries, aimed to explain the unique characteristics of living beings that could not be accounted for by physical and chemical processes alone. However, with the advancement of science, vitalism has been largely dismissed in favor of more mechanistic and materialistic explanations for the processes of life.

title: Gabriel Marcel
text: Gabriel Marcel (1889-1973) was a French existentialist philosopher, playwright, and Christian thinker. He is known for his emphasis on the importance of human experience and relationships, criticizing the dehumanizing effects of modern technology and materialism. Marcel's concept of "creative fidelity" stressed the need for individuals to engage authentically with others and the world around them. His influential works include "Being and Having," "The Mystery of Being," and "Man Against Mass Society." Marcel's ideas continue to be studied and debated by philosophers and theologians around the world.

title: Memorial Day
text: Memorial Day is a federal holiday in the United States dedicated to honoring and remembering the men and women who have died while serving in the country's armed forces. Observed on the last Monday in May, it is a time for Americans to pay tribute to those who made the ultimate sacrifice for their country. Many people visit cemeteries and memorials, hold parades, and participate in other patriotic activities to commemorate the day. It is also seen as the unofficial start of summer, with many people enjoying barbecues, beach trips, and other outdoor activities on this long weekend.

title: ARP spoofing
text: ARP spoofing is a malicious technique used to intercept network traffic. In this attack, a hacker sends fake Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) messages to redirect traffic to their own device. By posing as a legitimate network device, the attacker can intercept sensitive information like login credentials or monitor network activity. ARP spoofing can lead to various security threats, including man-in-the-middle attacks and data theft. To prevent ARP spoofing, network administrators can use techniques like ARP monitoring, static ARP entries, and network segmentation. Regularly monitoring network activity can also help detect and prevent ARP spoofing attacks.

title: Reference counting
text: Reference counting is a memory management technique used in computer programming. It involves keeping track of the number of references or pointers to a resource, such as an object in memory. When the reference count drops to zero, the resource is automatically deallocated or released. This ensures that memory leaks are avoided, as resources are only freed when they are no longer being used. Reference counting is a popular technique in languages like Objective-C and Python, where automatic memory management is desired. However, it does have limitations, such as difficulty in handling circular references.

title: Dynamic mechanical analysis
text: Dynamic mechanical analysis (DMA) is a technique used to study the mechanical properties of materials as a function of temperature, time, frequency, and other parameters. It measures the response of a material to an oscillating force, providing valuable information about its viscoelastic behavior. DMA is commonly used in research and industrial settings to characterize polymers, composites, and other materials, helping engineers and scientists understand their performance and durability. By analyzing the storage modulus, loss modulus, and damping properties of a material, DMA can provide insights into its structure and behavior under different conditions.

title: General Mobile Radio Service

GMRS radios are more powerful than FRS (Family Radio Service) radios, allowing for clearer communication over longer distances. In order to use GMRS, individuals must obtain a license from the Federal Communications Commission (FCC).

title: Sympathetic nervous system
text: The sympathetic nervous system is responsible for the body's fight-or-flight response to stressors. It activates in moments of danger, causing an increase in heart rate, dilation of the pupils, and a boost in energy levels. This system prepares the body to react quickly and effectively to threats. It works in coordination with the parasympathetic nervous system to maintain a balance in the body's autonomic functions. The sympathetic nervous system plays a crucial role in ensuring survival by initiating rapid physiological changes to help individuals confront or escape from potentially harmful situations.

title: New towns in the United Kingdom

title: Extreme ultraviolet Imaging Telescope
text: The Extreme Ultraviolet Imaging Telescope (EIT) is a scientific instrument used for observing solar activity in the extreme ultraviolet (EUV) spectrum. Developed by NASA, the EIT provides high-resolution images of the sun's outer atmosphere, or corona, allowing scientists to study solar flares, coronal mass ejections, and other phenomena that impact space weather. The EIT has been a vital tool in advancing our understanding of the sun and its effects on Earth's magnetosphere and ionosphere. This telescope has been essential for monitoring solar activity and its potential impacts on technology and communication systems.

title: Abductive reasoning
text: Abductive reasoning is a form of logical inference that involves forming the most likely explanation based on the available evidence. Unlike deductive reasoning, which guarantees a correct conclusion, abductive reasoning aims to find the most plausible solution, even if it is not certain. This type of reasoning is often used in scientific research, legal investigations, and everyday problem-solving. By considering all possible explanations and selecting the one that best fits the evidence, individuals can make informed decisions and draw meaningful conclusions.

title: Rachel Carson

Carson's legacy lives on as she is remembered as a pioneering voice for the protection of nature and the importance of environmental stewardship.

title: American Chemical Society

It is also involved in promoting public understanding of chemistry and advocating for the importance of chemistry in society. title: Apostles' Creed

The creed is used in both Catholic and Protestant traditions as a statement of faith and is recited in worship services and during baptismal ceremonies. title: SS Canberra

title: Biodefense
text: Biodefense is a multidisciplinary field that focuses on protecting against biological threats, including bioterrorism, infectious diseases, and pandemics. It encompasses measures such as vaccines, surveillance, rapid detection methods, and emergency response plans to mitigate the impact of biological agents on human, animal, and plant populations. Biodefense strategies are crucial in safeguarding public health, national security, and global stability. Researchers, healthcare professionals, government agencies, and policymakers collaborate to develop and implement comprehensive biodefense programs to prevent, prepare for, and respond to biological emergencies effectively.

title: Vehicle identification number
text: A vehicle identification number (VIN) is a unique code assigned to every vehicle and serves as its fingerprint. It typically consists of 17 characters, containing both letters and numbers, that provide detailed information about the car's manufacturer, model, and features. The VIN is used by law enforcement, insurance companies, and car dealerships to identify and track vehicles. It is also useful for consumers when purchasing a used car, as it can uncover important details about the vehicle's history and any potential issues.

title: Chariot
text: A chariot is a type of horse-drawn vehicle that was used in ancient civilizations for transportation and warfare. Typically, chariots had two wheels and were pulled by horses or other animals. They were often used by nobility and military commanders for battles and races. Chariots played a significant role in shaping ancient warfare tactics and were a symbol of power and status. The design and construction of chariots varied across different ancient civilizations, showcasing the ingenuity and craftsmanship of their creators. Today, chariots are mainly seen in historical reenactments and as props in movies and television

title: Stanford bunny
text: The Stanford bunny is a popular 3D model used in computer graphics and visualization. Created at Stanford University by Greg Turk and Marc Levoy in 1994, the bunny showcases the complexities of surface modeling and rendering techniques. With its distinctive shape and details, the Stanford bunny has become a standard benchmark in the field of computer graphics, helping researchers test and compare various algorithms and tools. title: RS-485
text: RS-485 is a standard defining the electrical characteristics of drivers and receivers for use in balanced digital multipoint systems. It is widely used in industrial automation and building control applications due to its robustness and noise immunity. RS-485 supports data rates up to 10 Mbps and allows multiple devices to communicate over long distances (up to 1200 meters) using a single twisted pair cable. Unlike RS-232, RS-485 can support multiple devices on the same bus, making it a popular choice for networked communication in various industries.

title: Jan Baptist van Helmont

His contributions to chemistry and biology laid the groundwork for future research in these fields, earning him a lasting legacy in the history of science.

title: Mound Bayou, Mississippi

title: Automatic double tracking
text: Automatic double tracking is a recording technique used in music production to create a fuller, richer sound. It involves duplicating a performance and slightly altering the timing or pitch of the duplicate track to create a natural doubling effect. This technique is often used in rock, pop, and electronic music to add depth and enhance the overall sound quality of a recording. Automatic double tracking can be achieved using specialized software or hardware, making it a popular tool for producers and engineers looking to create professional-sounding mixes.

title: Margaret Cole

title: Tidal resonance
text: Tidal resonance is a phenomenon where an oscillating system's natural frequency coincides with the frequency of an external periodic force, leading to a significant increase in amplitude. In the case of tides, tidal resonance occurs when the period of the tide matches the natural period of a body of water, such as a bay or estuary. This can result in a dramatic amplification of tidal currents and water level fluctuations in these areas. Tidal resonance plays a crucial role in shaping coastal environments and can have significant impacts on navigation, erosion, and ecosystem health.

title: Biosensor
text: A biosensor is an analytical device that detects biological substances, such as enzymes, antibodies, or DNA, by converting the biological response into an electrical signal. These devices are widely used in various fields, including healthcare, food safety, and environmental monitoring. Biosensors offer quick and accurate results, making them valuable tools for detecting diseases, monitoring glucose levels, and identifying pathogens. They are designed to be portable, cost-effective, and easy to use, making them ideal for on-site testing. With their ability to provide real-time data, biosensors are essential in improving diagnostics and disease management.

title: Brunswick, Georgia

title: Crème de Noyaux

The resulting liqueur has a distinct nutty taste with hints of bitter almond and stone fruit. Crème de Noyaux is commonly used in cocktails as a flavoring agent or added to desserts for a sweet and nutty twist. title: PIT maneuver
text: The PIT maneuver, which stands for Precision Immobilization Technique, is a law enforcement driving tactic used to stop fleeing vehicles. By nudging the rear bumper of a fleeing vehicle with the front bumper of a police vehicle, the pursuing officer can cause the suspect's vehicle to spin out of control and ultimately stop. This maneuver is considered a safe and effective way to end high-speed pursuits while minimizing the risk of injury to both officers and suspects. The PIT maneuver is a widely-used technique in police departments around the world for apprehending fleeing suspects.

title: Messenger RNA

Monitoring and improving VO2 max can lead to enhanced performance in endurance sports and overall health benefits.

title: Hors d'oeuvre
text: Hors d'oeuvre, also known as appetizers, are small, bite-sized dishes served before the main course of a meal. They can be hot or cold, and are meant to stimulate the appetite and tantalize the taste buds. Common examples include bruschetta, cheese platters, and mini quiches. Hors d'oeuvre can be simple or elaborate, depending on the occasion. They are often served at parties, gatherings, and events where guests can mingle and enjoy a variety of flavors before the main meal is served.

title: Study of the Hebrew language
text: The study of the Hebrew language dates back thousands of years and holds significant cultural and religious importance. Hebrew is the language of the Jewish people and the official language of Israel. It is written from right to left and consists of 22 consonants. The study of Hebrew includes learning the alphabet, grammar, vocabulary, and pronunciation. Many people around the world study Hebrew for religious, academic, or personal reasons. By studying Hebrew, individuals gain a deeper understanding of Jewish texts, history, and traditions. Overall, the study of Hebrew is a valuable pursuit for those interested in Jewish culture and language.

title: Mercury dime
text: The Mercury dime, also known as the Winged Liberty Head dime, was a ten-cent coin produced by the United States Mint from 1916 to 1945. Designed by Adolph Weinman, the coin features a portrait of Liberty wearing a winged cap on the obverse, and a Roman fasces on the reverse. Despite its common name, the coin does not actually depict the Roman god Mercury. The Mercury dime is highly collectible and sought after by numismatists for its classic design and historical significance.

title: Go Seigen
text: Go Seigen was a Chinese-born, Japanese Go player who is considered one of the greatest players in the history of the game. He was known for his innovative playing style and deep understanding of strategy. Go Seigen played a crucial role in establishing Go as a highly respected game in Japan and helped to popularize it around the world. His influence on modern Go is still felt today, and many top players continue to study his games for inspiration.

title: Origins of the American Civil War
text: The American Civil War was a conflict fought in the United States from 1861 to 1865. Its origins can be traced back to deep-rooted social, economic, and political tensions that divided the North and South. The primary issue was slavery, with Southern states seceding to protect their right to own slaves. The election of anti-slavery Abraham Lincoln as President in 1860 further escalated tensions, leading to the secession of several Southern states and the formation of the Confederate States of America. The Civil War ultimately ended with the defeat of the Confederacy and the abolishment of slavery

title: Heliox
text: Heliox is a breathing gas mixture of helium and oxygen commonly used in medical settings to treat patients with respiratory conditions. Due to its low density, heliox enables easier breathing for individuals with obstructive airway diseases such as asthma or chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. The use of heliox can reduce the work of breathing and improve ventilation in these patients. In addition to medical applications, heliox is also used in diving, aviation, and other industries where respiratory gas mixtures are necessary.

title: Volksdeutsche
text: Volksdeutsche refers to ethnic Germans residing outside of Germany. During the early 20th century, many Volksdeutsche were living in Eastern Europe and were sometimes seen as a potential Fifth Column by those countries where they resided. After World War II, many Volksdeutsche were expelled from Eastern Europe as part of the post-war territorial changes. Today, the term Volksdeutsche is sometimes used to refer to Germans who have settled or have ancestry in other countries, particularly in Eastern Europe.

title: Ferris Township, Michigan
text: Ferris Township is a small rural community located in Osceola County, Michigan. The township was established in 1873 and named after Woodbridge N. Ferris, a former Governor of Michigan and founder of Ferris State University. With a population of around 3,000 residents, Ferris Township offers a peaceful and scenic environment, surrounded by farmland and forests. Residents enjoy outdoor activities such as hunting, fishing, and hiking, as well as community events and festivals throughout the year. Ferris Township is known for its friendly atmosphere and strong sense of community spirit.
